SIMPLE: pounce
RECORDS: 5

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Pounce
<hw>Pounce</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[F. <ets>ponce</ets>
pumice, pounce, fr. L. <ets>pumex</ets>, <ets>-icis</ets>, pumice. See
<er>Pumice</er>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>A fine powder, as of sandarac,
or cuttlefish bone, -- formerly used to prevent ink from spreading on
manuscript.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><-- p. 1122 --></p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>Charcoal dust, or some other colored powder for
making patterns through perforated designs, -- used by embroiderers,
lace makers, etc.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>Pounce box</b></col>, <cd>a box for sprinkling
pounce.</cd> -- <col><b>Pounce paper</b></col>, <cd>a transparent paper
for tracing.</cd></cs>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Pounce</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Pounce
<hw>Pounce</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <vmorph>[<pos>imp. & p.
p.</pos> <conjf>Pounded</conjf> <pr>(?)</pr>; <pos>p. pr. & vb. n.</pos>
<conjf>Pouncing</conjf> <pr>(?)</pr>.]</vmorph> <def>To sprinkle or rub
with pounce; <as>as, to <ex>pounce</ex> paper, or a
pattern</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Pounce</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 3 ====
HEADWORD: Pounce
<hw>Pounce</hw>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[Prob. through French, from an
assumed LL. <ets>punctiare</ets> to prick, L. <ets>pungere</ets>,
<ets>punctum</ets>. See <er>Puncheon</er>, <er>Punch</er>, <pos>v.
t.</pos>]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>The claw or talon of a bird of
prey.</def> <rj><au>Spenser. Burke.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>A punch or stamp.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark> ⟦ldquo⟧A
<xex>pounce</xex> to print money with.⟦rdquo⟧
<rj><au>Withals.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>Cloth worked in eyelet holes.</def>
<mark>[Obs.]</mark> <rj><au>Homilies.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Pounce</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 4 ====
HEADWORD: Pounce
<hw>Pounce</hw>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <sn>1.</sn> <def>To strike or seize
with the talons; to pierce, as with the talons.</def>
<mark>[Archaic]</mark>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Stooped from his highest pitch to <qex>pounce</qex> a wren.</q>
<rj><qau>Cowper.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Now <qex>pounce</qex> him lightly,⟦br⟧
And as he roars and rages, let's go deeper.</q> <rj><qau>J.
Fletcher.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>To punch; to perforate; to stamp holes in, or dots
on, by way of ornament.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark> <rj><au>Sir T.
Elyot.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Pounce</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 5 ====
HEADWORD: Pounce
<hw>Pounce</hw>, <pos>v. i.</pos> <def>To fall suddenly and seize with
the claws; -- with <xex>on</xex> or <xex>upon</xex>; <as>as, a hawk
<ex>pounces</ex> upon a chicken</as>. Also used figuratively.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Derision is never so agonizing as when it <qex>pounces</qex> on
the wanderings of misguided sensibility.</q>
<rj><qau>Jeffrey.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Pounced</ent>⟦br⟧
